Oukp8sTGDn7QZ2An2YyK29iVGLwzKsCUx4hx-WNY58uHkSq7t8Nk3-CtsQ__Y3MtJiYVq-dz8VRYjtxo3RXOOs77vHf3cRcJNWyo_ygGdfrxHUZPv6Dj2zGgHSsu51bHLAc8yhJ6oV2U3nF7chs0JsnIHrjntNbSZFmC6LZxkTKoZaj_tJzhyooOgNobJCtF2FxMQkthp8bHfmTsL6QM-FjRGC1ShaksZBhaIo37-9HRIcrchKSzv9jpvLR_iNUZ4k8Ku0sLodUQbSPIDtdGM6Ouo5_snx9PEfWWU6XAnaCh3tvnK3G3wDPqoOMSYtcyGmz0K3ZMgtZaQIgyPYijTjlguak0UzvAigmw4Gi3sTWWmWhOPTpcYdTuoJsX4DVUmp8tmtm_0uo=\",\"summary\":[{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating class loading options**\\n\\nI’m considering using Java’s `URLClassLoader` as a public class loading API for testing dynamic class loading. The user’s request includes loading classes and catching errors, but directly using reflection may lead to contamination. Instead, I think it’s better to implement a `Runnable` helper that can load a child class. However, reflections for testing purposes seem tricky. I might look into using `ClassLoader.loadClass` to avoid unnecessary initialization. It feels a bit complicated, but possible!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Exploring class loading alternatives**\\n\\nThe user mentioned not to use reflection directly, so I’m considering using `URLClassLoader.findClass` as an alternative. I could define the class to resolve it without initialization. I’m also thinking about the `ServiceLoader.load` method, which requires including a service file. To do this, the helper class must implement the service interface. I’ll check if Gradle tests allow including resources, and potentially add a service provider file under `src/test/resources/META-INF/services/`. It’s a bit broad, but worth exploring!\"},{\"type\":\"summary_text\",\"text\":\"**Evaluating Javassist functionality**\\n\\nI’m considering if the Javassist source compiler allows for a `$` method. I need to check a specific source string I have: a method called `lookup` that returns a class using `javassist.ClassPool.class$`. In Java, the `$` character is allowed in class names. Since the method has package access a